'''''Caveman Ughlympics''''' or '''''Caveman Ugh-lympics''''' is a 1988 [[Olympic video games|Olympic-themed]] [[sports game|sports]] [[video game]] set in the [[Stone Age]]. It was developed for the [[Commodore 64]] and [[MS-DOS]] by [[Dynamix]] and published by [[Electronic Arts]]. The [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] version was [[Porting|ported]] and released by Data East USA, a subsidiary of [[Data East]], as '''''Caveman Games'''''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Caveman Ugh-Lympics (NES) Back Cover|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/nes/caveman-ugh-lympics/cover-art/gameCoverId,247159/|website=[[MobyGames]]|date=August 4, 2012|accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref>

==Gameplay==
''Caveman Ughlympics'' is a [[Stone Age]] [[Olympic Games|Olympics]] played using different combinations of keys on the player's keyboard or the NES controller. The game is made up of six events:
*'''Saber Race''', where the player races against an opponent avoiding both obstacles and the [[Smilodon|sabre tooth tiger]] running behind.
*'''Matetoss''', similar to the [[hammer throw]], where the player has to spin their wife/husband and try to throw them as far as they can.
*'''Firemaking''', where the player races an opponent to create a full-burning fire.
*'''Clubbing''', where the player faces off against an opponent holding clubs on a cliff, trying to club the other off the cliff sides or deplete their [[life meter]].
*'''Dino Race''', where the player sits on a dinosaur and races against an opponent, avoiding obstacles on the course.
*'''Dino Vault''', where the player has to [[pole vault]] over a ''[[Tyrannosaurus|Tyrannosaurus rex]]''.

==Reception==
''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' gave the game a positive review, saying the game is most enjoyable with 2-4 players. The game's humor was its most praised quality.<ref name="CGW"/>{{verify source|date=August 2023|reason=There is no such article in the Jan 1989 issue of CGW, and the article with that name and by-line is from 1984, predating the game}}

David Wilson reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that "the next time you find yourself longing for those simpler times and looking for a way to sate the barbarian within, don't lose your cool—boot up ''Caveman Ughlympics'' instead."<ref name="CGW57">{{cite magazine |last=Wilson |first=David |title=Neanderthal Nonsense and Cro-Magnon Comedy |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=March 1989 |volume=1 |issue=57 |pages=43–44}}</ref>

